⚖️ LCES: Legal Calculus Educational System

🟦 Domain-Specific Editions and Risk Profiles

LCES recognizes a practical truth:

Different legal environments create different failure risks.

A small claims case does not break down the same way a family court dispute does.

A trust or estate matter does not require the same structure as a simple debt claim.

That is why LCES uses domain-specific editions.

🔹 Small Claims Edition — SC-LCES

Focus:

- 📄 High-volume disputes

• ⚖️ Lower-complexity claims

• 🧾 Pro se usability

Typical risks:

- Missing evidence

• Weak chronology

• Procedural informality hiding defects

Goal:

✅ Minimum viable procedural action.

🔹 Family Court Edition — FC-LCES

Focus:

- 👨‍👩‍👧 Custody

• 💵 Support

• 🗓️ Parenting time

• 🛡️ Safety-sensitive issues

Typical risks:

- Narrative overload

• Emotion-driven structure failure

• Missing safety facts

• Unclear requested relief

Goal:

✅ Procedural stability, clarity, and safety-sensitive intake.

🔹 Trust & Estate Edition — TE-LCES

Focus:

- 🏛️ Probate

• 📜 Trusts

• 🤝 Fiduciary duties

• 🧩 Multi-party disputes

Typical risks:

- Role confusion

• Timeline ambiguity

• Asset-path confusion

• Complexity drift across parties

Goal:

✅ Structured escalation for multi-party complexity.

🟨 The core insight:

LCES does not force every legal problem into the same template.

It adapts to the forum, the dispute type, and the risk profile.

Because procedural engineering is not just about drafting.

It is about designing the workflow around the failure patterns most likely to appear.

⚖️ Different domains.

Different risks.

Different intake architecture.

Same commitment to a defensible record.

